      "topic_id": "coordinate_systems",
      "title": "Coordinate Systems",
      "order": 1,
      "explanation": {
        "simple": "A coordinate system is a way to describe the position of any point in space using numbers. The Cartesian system uses perpendicular x, y (and z in 3D) axes with an origin at (0,0). Other systems like polar coordinates use distance and angle instead. Choosing the right coordinate system can make problems much easier to solve!",
        "advanced": "Coordinate systems provide a systematic framework for locating points in space. The Cartesian (rectangular) system uses orthogonal axes with basis vectors ├о, ─╡, k╠В. Polar coordinates (r, ╬╕) are useful for radially symmetric problems тАФ conversion: x = r cos╬╕, y = r sin╬╕. In 3D, cylindrical (r, ╬╕, z) and spherical (r, ╬╕, ╧Ж) coordinates extend these concepts. The Jacobian determinant handles area/volume element transformations between systems. Each system has its own expression for gradient, divergence, curl, and Laplacian operators."
      },
      "formulas": [
        {
          "name": "Cartesian to Polar",
          "latex": "r = \\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}, \\quad \\theta = \\arctan\\left(\\frac{y}{x}\\right)",
          "variables": {
            "r": {"description": "Radial distance from origin", "unit": ""},
            "╬╕": {"description": "Angle from positive x-axis", "unit": "rad"}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Polar to Cartesian",
          "latex": "x = r\\cos\\theta, \\quad y = r\\sin\\theta",
          "variables": {}
        },
        {
          "name": "3D Cartesian Distance",
          "latex": "d = \\sqrt{(x_2-x_1)^2 + (y_2-y_1)^2 + (z_2-z_1)^2}",
          "variables": {}
        },
        {
          "name": "Spherical to Cartesian",
          "latex": "x = r\\sin\\phi\\cos\\theta, \\quad y = r\\sin\\phi\\sin\\theta, \\quad z = r\\cos\\phi",
          "variables": {
            "╧Ж": {"description": "Polar angle (from z-axis)", "unit": "rad"},
            "╬╕": {"description": "Azimuthal angle (from x-axis in xy-plane)", "unit": "rad"}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Jacobian (Polar)",
          "latex": "dA = r\\, dr\\, d\\theta",
          "variables": {}
        }
      ],
