    {
      "topic_id": "function_graphs",
      "title": "Function Graphs & Transformations",
      "order": 3,
      "explanation": {
        "simple": "A graph is a visual picture of a mathematical function тАФ it shows how one quantity changes with another. The graph of y = x┬▓ is a parabola, y = sin(x) is a wave, and y = 1/x is a hyperbola. You can transform graphs by shifting, stretching, reflecting, or rotating them. Understanding graphs helps you see patterns and solve equations visually!",
        "advanced": "Functions f: тДЭ тЖТ тДЭ are visualized as curves in the Cartesian plane {(x, f(x)) | x тИИ domain(f)}. Transformations include: vertical shift f(x) + k, horizontal shift f(x - h), vertical stretch af(x), horizontal stretch f(bx), and reflections -f(x) or f(-x). Critical analysis involves: domain/range, intercepts, symmetry (even/odd), asymptotes, continuity, differentiability, monotonicity (f' > 0 increasing), concavity (f'' > 0 concave up), extrema (f' = 0, f'' test), and inflection points (f'' = 0). Parametric forms (x(t), y(t)) and implicit forms F(x,y) = 0 extend the representation."
      },
      "formulas": [
        {
          "name": "Linear Function",
          "latex": "f(x) = mx + c",
          "variables": {
            "m": {"description": "Slope (rate of change)", "unit": ""},
            "c": {"description": "y-intercept", "unit": ""}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Quadratic Function",
          "latex": "f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c",
          "variables": {
            "vertex": {"description": "(-b/2a, f(-b/2a))", "unit": ""},
            "discriminant": {"description": "╬Ф = b┬▓ - 4ac", "unit": ""}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Vertex Form",
          "latex": "f(x) = a(x - h)^2 + k",
          "variables": {
            "(h, k)": {"description": "Vertex coordinates", "unit": ""},
            "a": {"description": "Controls width and direction of parabola", "unit": ""}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Sine Function",
          "latex": "f(x) = A\\sin(Bx + C) + D",
          "variables": {
            "A": {"description": "Amplitude", "unit": ""},
