      "explanation": {
        "simple": "Just like 2D graphs show functions of one variable, 3D surfaces show functions of two variables: z = f(x, y). A bowl shape (paraboloid), a saddle shape, a sphere, and a torus (donut) are all 3D surfaces. Parametric curves let you trace paths through 3D space by defining x, y, and z as functions of a single parameter t.",
        "advanced": "Surfaces in тДЭ┬│ are 2-manifolds defined implicitly F(x,y,z) = 0, explicitly z = f(x,y), or parametrically r(u,v) = (x(u,v), y(u,v), z(u,v)). Key surfaces: plane (ax+by+cz=d), sphere (x┬▓+y┬▓+z┬▓ = r┬▓), ellipsoid, paraboloid (z = x┬▓+y┬▓), hyperboloid, cylinder, cone, torus. Differential geometry studies curvature (Gaussian K = ╬║тВБ╬║тВВ, mean H = (╬║тВБ+╬║тВВ)/2). Parametric space curves r(t) = (x(t), y(t), z(t)) have tangent T╠В = r'/|r'|, normal N╠В, binormal B╠В = T╠В ├Ч N╠В (Frenet-Serret frame), curvature ╬║ = |r' ├Ч r''|/|r'|┬│."
